WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.280
Hi everyone, my name is Alex Farach. Welcome to Let's Start at the Beginning, Bits to Character

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:14.920
Encoding in R. I'm a data scientist and analytics manager at Accenture Federal Services. I spend

00:00:14.920 --> 00:00:20.120
a lot of time thinking about R, NLP, data viz, and statistical learning. My most recent

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:25.600
work is on the Hugging Face R package to bring hugging face models and tools to R. So how

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:30.280
would you describe the letter A to a computer? Today, I'll discuss how. In doing so, we'll

00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:35.740
get into the shallow end of a deep pool known as bits to character encoding. And we'll talk

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:39.939
a little bit about what that looks like in R. So what do we mean by bits to character

00:00:39.939 --> 00:00:44.480
encoding, especially in relationship to NLP? Well, computers don't speak the same language

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:48.939
as we do. If we want to use computers as a process language, we need some way to encode

00:00:48.939 --> 00:00:53.860
language so that computers understand and vice versa. Both the encoding and decoding

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:59.299
process needs to be identical on both ends or the human computer translation falls apart.

00:00:59.299 --> 00:01:04.779
The agreed upon method is called a protocol. So back to the question, how would you describe

00:01:04.779 --> 00:01:08.860
the letter A to a computer? Oh, we do so by using numbers, of course, to represent letters.

00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:14.220
So instead of A, we could have one, B could be two, and so on. We assign a number to represent

00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:19.300
each unique character or symbol we want to communicate. Computer store numbers in binary,

00:01:19.860 --> 00:01:24.500
and all signals inside a computer have two possible values, zero or one. Each of the

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:29.459
zero one pieces of information are called bits. One bit can represent two value, two bits can

00:01:29.459 --> 00:01:34.180
represent four, three bits represent eight, and so on. So how many bits is needed to represent

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:41.540
256 values? Using the logic just discussed, it's eight bits. When computers were first developed,

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:46.019
the decision was made that a byte was the next standard unit above a bit. A byte is defined as

00:01:46.019 --> 00:01:52.580
eight bits. In the 1960s, computer developers had one byte to work with. They developed a

00:01:52.580 --> 00:01:58.099
protocol to fit into this one byte called ASCII. This protocol can assign a unique number to all

00:01:58.099 --> 00:02:03.540
letters in the English language, plus numbers, symbols, and control characters. Everything fits

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:08.979
into this one byte budget, and even better, seven of the available eight bits were needed.

00:02:08.979 --> 00:02:13.220
Over time, the need to fit more information grew larger, but luckily, there was that extra bit to

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:18.820
work with. Things got standardized into Latin one, which uses a full eight bits available in

00:02:18.820 --> 00:02:25.380
the single byte. So then after that, a new standard was developed, UTF-8. Each character in UTF-8 is

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:31.139
represented using a prefix U followed by a four digit hexadecimal number. The difference between

00:02:31.139 --> 00:02:35.779
binary and hexadecimal numbers are out of scope for this brief talk. What's important to note

00:02:35.779 --> 00:02:41.699
here though is that UTF-8 converts a code point or a single character in Unicode into a set of one

00:02:41.699 --> 00:02:48.179
to four bytes and can encode all one million plus Unicode code points. Character strings in R can

00:02:48.179 --> 00:02:53.860
be encoded in Latin one, UTF-8, or as raw bytes. These declarations can be read or changed using

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:59.059
the encoding function. The concept of native encoding is important here. Natively encoded

00:02:59.059 --> 00:03:05.779
strings are strings written in whatever code page the user is using. As of the 4.2.0 release, R uses

00:03:05.779 --> 00:03:11.380
UTF-8 as the native encoding. Prior to this release, that was not the case because Windows

00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:17.380
versions prior to Windows 10 didn't allow it. Post Windows 10, this was allowed and R was updated to

00:03:17.380 --> 00:03:23.539
take advantage of this feature. This is an exciting change for us focusing on NLP and R since it

00:03:23.539 --> 00:03:28.979
mitigates a lot of potential problems for common NLP tasks. It's also helpful to keep this in mind

00:03:28.979 --> 00:03:36.259
when using common functions like read.csv where character encoding can be set. On Linux and

00:03:36.259 --> 00:03:42.100
macOS, the native encoding has been UTF-8 so this isn't an issue there. Native encoding is why we

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:47.539
see unknown here as well. For example, we see coffee as unknown even though it's clearly ASCII

00:03:47.539 --> 00:03:52.500
compliant. ASCII strings will never be marked with a declared encoding since their representation

00:03:53.300 --> 00:03:58.419
is the same in all supported encodings. The sys.getlocal function will tell you what your

00:03:58.419 --> 00:04:04.740
native encoding is. The localization information function is another helpful function. And lastly,

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:10.339
we have the iconvert function which uses system facilities to convert a character vector between

00:04:10.339 --> 00:04:16.739
encodings. So how does a tidyverse tackle encoding? We turn to the stringer library which is built on

00:04:16.739 --> 00:04:22.739
top of the extensive, excuse me, stringy package. We can specify the encoding of a string with the

00:04:22.739 --> 00:04:28.100
string convert function and for fun let's create a little function here that applies a random

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:34.660
encoding via the stringiStringEncodeList function. And that's it. Thanks for hanging out with me.

